[ProMED-mail thanks Prof Thomas Loescher and colleagues for reporting these 2 cases of _Plasmodium knowlesi_ and alerting us to this emerging infection in the Southeast Asia.

_Plasmodium knowlesi_ is found in all countries in Southeast Asia where there are Macaque monkeys, which are the natural reservoirs.

_P. knowlesi_ was previously classified as _P. malariae_, but with the development of molecular typing of the plasmodia, it became apparent that many malaria infections previously classified as _P. malariae_ were indeed _P. knowlesi_.

Infection with _P. knowlesi_ is dangerous because the life-cycle of the parasite is only 24 hours and the parasitemia therefore increases more rapidly compared to the other malaria species.

So far transmission is from the macaques to humans, and human-to-human transmission has, to our knowledge, not been found. - Mod.EP

For the HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Germany, see https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3091357,101 and of Thailand, see https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3091357,151.
- Mod.EP]
